      <div id="related-links" class="related-links">
        <h2>Around the Web</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="http://www.filmcomment.com/entry/interview-david-fincher
" target="_blank">
              <h5>Film Comment: Interview with David Fincher</h5>
              <p>"I don’t think Gillian [Flynn] is a misogynist. She’s taking everybody to task in a very subtle way."</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Film Comment</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/oct/03/gone-girl-phenomenon-gillian-flynn
" target="_blank">
              <h5>The Gone Girl phenomenon: Gillian Flynn speaks out</h5>
              <p>Flynn talks about her leap to fame, writing the screenplay of the new film, and why no one should read her dark books expecting to find a likable character</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> The Guardian</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.filmcomment.com/entry/bombast-gone-finching
" target="_blank">
              <h5>Bombast: Gone Finching</h5>
              <p>For all of Fincher’s marvelous control, I can’t look past the accumulation of Nineties tropes that riddle his filmography, a particular form of PTSD that comes with having gone through adolescence in that era.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Nick Pinkerton, Film Comment</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/david-finchers-portrait-marriage" target="_blank">
              <h5>David Fincher's portrait of a marriage</h5>
              <p>“Gone Girl” is David Fincher’s “Eyes Wide Shut.” As Stanley Kubrick did in his final film, Fincher lifts the lid off the black box of marriage.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Richard Brody, The New Yorker</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://cinema-scope.com/currency/pursuits-happiness-david-finchers-gone-girl/" target="_blank">
              <h5>Pursuits of happiness</h5>
              <p>"Gone Girl"’s portrait of domestic bliss as a kind of personalized thermonuclear détente is glib and obvious, but it’s also deeply satisfying.</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Adam Nayman, cinema scope</p>
            </a>
          </li><li>
            <a href="http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/dec/04/gone-girl-hard-work-marriage/" target="_blank">
              <h5>The hard work of marriage</h5>
              <p>The belief that conjugal happiness can be earned only by rigorous and sustained emotional labor is so deeply entrenched in the common culture that when Amy Dunne boasts cheerfully of finding marriage “easy,” it is as if she had entered Dracula’s castle scoffing at the existence of vampires: the audience knows at once that her hubris must be punished.
</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> Zoë Heller, The New York Review of Books</p>
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
